40. Nat Commun. 2018 Aug 1;9(1):3012. doi: 10.1038/s41467-018-05429-5.Plk1 overexpression induces chromosomal instability and suppresses tumordevelopment.de Cárcer G(1), Venkateswaran SV(2)(3), Salgueiro L(2), El Bakkali A(4), Somogyi K(2), Rowald K(2), Montañés P(4), Sanclemente M(4), Escobar B(4), de MartinoA(5), McGranahan N(6), Malumbres M(7), Sotillo R(8)(9).Author information: (1)Cell Division and Cancer Group, Spanish National Cancer Research Centre(CNIO), Melchor Fernández Almagro 3, E-28029, Madrid, Spain. gcarcer@cnio.es.(2)Division of Molecular Thoracic Oncology, German Cancer Research Center (DKFZ),Im Neuenheimer Feld 280, 69120, Heidelberg, Germany.(3)Faculty of Biosciences, Heidelberg University, 69117, Heidelberg, Germany.(4)Cell Division and Cancer Group, Spanish National Cancer Research Centre(CNIO), Melchor Fernández Almagro 3, E-28029, Madrid, Spain.(5)Histopathology Unit, Spanish National Cancer Research Centre (CNIO), 28029,Madrid, Spain.(6)Cancer Research UK Lung Cancer Center of Excellence, University College LondonCancer Institute, Paul O'Gorman Building, 72 Huntley Street, London, WC1E 6BT,UK.(7)Cell Division and Cancer Group, Spanish National Cancer Research Centre(CNIO), Melchor Fernández Almagro 3, E-28029, Madrid, Spain. malumbres@cnio.es.(8)Division of Molecular Thoracic Oncology, German Cancer Research Center (DKFZ),Im Neuenheimer Feld 280, 69120, Heidelberg, Germany.r.sotillo@dkfz-heidelberg.de.(9)Translational Lung Research Center Heidelberg (TRLC), German Center for LungResearch (DZL), Heidelberg, Germany. r.sotillo@dkfz-heidelberg.de.Polo-like kinase 1 (Plk1) is overexpressed in a wide spectrum of human tumors,being frequently considered as an oncogene and an attractive cancer target.However, its contribution to tumor development is unclear. Using a new inducible knock-in mouse model we report here that Plk1 overexpression results in abnormal chromosome segregation and cytokinesis, generating polyploid cells with reducedproliferative potential. Mechanistically, these cytokinesis defects correlatewith defective loading of Cep55 and ESCRT complexes to the abscission bridge, in a Plk1 kinase-dependent manner. In vivo, Plk1 overexpression prevents thedevelopment of Kras-induced and Her2-induced mammary gland tumors, in thepresence of increased rates of chromosome instability. In patients, Plk1overexpression correlates with improved survival in specific breast cancersubtypes. Therefore, despite the therapeutic benefits of inhibiting Plk1 due toits essential role in tumor cell cycles, Plk1 overexpression hastumor-suppressive properties by perturbing mitotic progression and cytokinesis.DOI: 10.1038/s41467-018-05429-5 PMCID: PMC6070485PMID: 30069007 